methodsArray.push( [ 'CostanzoRecipes_Entrees_SweetPotatoHash', '<p><ol><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> To par-boil the sweet potatoes place them in <amount original_amount="a medium" fraction="1.000000000000" units="medium">a medium</amount>-sized pot and cover with water, add the <amount original_amount="½ teaspoon" fraction="0.500000000000" units="teaspoon">½ teaspoon</amount> of salt, stir. Bring to a boil, uncovered, and boil for 2 to 3 minutes. The potatoes should be slightly tender, but not completely cooked. A fork should go about ⅓ of the way into the potato. Once they are par-boiled immediately drain them in to a colander and rinse them in cold water to stop the cooking process. Set aside.<img src="images/alarm-clock-icon.png" onclick="toggleElement(\'CircularTimer-1\')" class="alarm-clock-icon"><div id="CircularTimer-1" class="circular-timer-container"><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-1", 120)</script><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-1", 180)</script></div></li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> While the sweet potatoes are coming to a boil sauté the mushrooms. Heat <amount original_amount="a large" fraction="1.000000000000" units="large">a large</amount>, heavy-bottomed skillet over medium-high heat. Melt the butter. Add the mushrooms and sauté them for about 10 minutes, stirring occasionally. They should be browned and tender. Remove the mushrooms into a dish and set aside.<img src="images/alarm-clock-icon.png" onclick="toggleElement(\'CircularTimer-2\')" class="alarm-clock-icon"><div id="CircularTimer-2" class="circular-timer-container"><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-2", 600)</script></div></li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Heat the grapeseed oil in the heated skillet, add the onion and the Fresno chili or jalapeno (optional). Sauté until tender, about 3 minutes. Add the garlic and sauté for 1 minute more. <img src="images/alarm-clock-icon.png" onclick="toggleElement(\'CircularTimer-3\')" class="alarm-clock-icon"><div id="CircularTimer-3" class="circular-timer-container"><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-3", 180)</script><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-3", 60)</script></div></li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Add the red bell pepper and the par-boiled sweet potatoes. Season with a healthy pinch of salt and pepper. Sauté for about 10 to 15 minutes, stirring occasionally. You will know the potatoes are done when they are fork-tender and slightly caramelized. Add the mushrooms back into the hot pan and allow to heat for 2 minutes. <img src="images/alarm-clock-icon.png" onclick="toggleElement(\'CircularTimer-4\')" class="alarm-clock-icon"><div id="CircularTimer-4" class="circular-timer-container"><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-4", 600)</script><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-4", 900)</script><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-4", 120)</script></div></li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Remove the pan from the heat and stir in the cilantro. Taste-test and add more salt and pepper as needed. Transfer the sweet potato mixture onto <amount original_amount="a serving" fraction="1.000000000000" units="serving">a serving</amount> platter or individual plates.</li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Return to the skillet, heat over medium-high heat. Add <amount original_amount="a tablespoon" fraction="1.000000000000" units="tablespoon">a tablespoon</amount> of grapeseed oil. Crack as many eggs as you plan to use into the skillet. Cover and cook for about 3 to 5 minutes, or until the egg white has set and the yolk is still runny. NOTE: you can cook your eggs any way you prefer, but I recommend eggs that have runny yolks for this recipe so that the potatoes can soak everything up.<img src="images/alarm-clock-icon.png" onclick="toggleElement(\'CircularTimer-5\')" class="alarm-clock-icon"><div id="CircularTimer-5" class="circular-timer-container"><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-5", 180)</script><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-5", 300)</script></div></li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Serve the eggs over the potato hash mixture with a side of ketchup and Sriracha sauce (optional). </li></ol>' ] );
