creditsArray.push( [ 'CostanzoRecipes_Entrees_PizzaCrustSourdoughKingArthur', '<p><ul><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> created [2019-12-12 Thu]   </li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"><a href="https://www.kingarthurflour.com/recipes/sourdough-pizza-crust-recipe" target="_blank">https://www.kingarthurflour.com/recipes/sourdough-pizza-crust-recipe</a>  </li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)">[2019-12-15 Sun]  Made one pie from this. The dough handled really well and had a nice flavor. But it should have been thinner. Also, the cheese (fresh mozerella) didn\'t brown. Try parbaking the crust for a shorter time.  </li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)">[2020-02-09 Sun]  Made one mushroom pie. Preheated oven with the pizza stone to 550 degrees for an hour and left it there. Fully assembled pie and baked for ~8(?) minutes. Nice browning; not crispy but good. T said it was probably the best I ever did. <img src="images/alarm-clock-icon.png" onclick="toggleElement(\'CircularTimer-10\')" class="alarm-clock-icon"><div id="CircularTimer-10" class="circular-timer-container"><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-10", 3600)</script><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-10", 0)</script></div></li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)">[2020-03-11 Wed]  Made one mushroom pie. Preheated oven with the pizza stone to 550 degrees for > an hour and left it there. Fully assembled pie and baked for 3 minutes, then rotated the pie and baked for another 3 minutes. Then I turned broil on for a couple of minutes. Nice browning and crispy. T said it was probably the <img src="images/alarm-clock-icon.png" onclick="toggleElement(\'CircularTimer-11\')" class="alarm-clock-icon"><div id="CircularTimer-11" class="circular-timer-container"><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-11", 3600)</script><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-11", 180)</script><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-11", 180)</script><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-11", 120)</script></div><i>second</i> best I ever did (I thought it was the best). </li></ul>' ] );
ingredientsArray.push( [ 'CostanzoRecipes_Entrees_PizzaCrustSourdoughAlexandra', '<p><ul><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> <amount original_amount="100 g" fraction="100.000000000000" units="g">100 g</amount> sourdough starter, active and bubbly</li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> <amount original_amount="375 g" fraction="375.000000000000" units="g">375 g</amount> water</li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> <amount original_amount="10 g" fraction="10.000000000000" units="g">10 g</amount> salt</li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> <amount original_amount="500 g" fraction="500.000000000000" units="g">500 g</amount> all-purpose or bread flour</li></ul>' ] );
methodsArray.push( [ 'CostanzoRecipes_Entrees_PizzaCrustSourdoughAlexandra', '<p><ol><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Combine <amount original_amount="15 g" fraction="15.000000000000" units="g">15 g</amount> of starter with <amount original_amount="15 g" fraction="15.000000000000" units="g">15 g</amount> of flour and <amount original_amount="15 g" fraction="15.000000000000" units="g">15 g</amount> of water in a bowl. Stir, cover and set aside at room temperature for ~12 hours.<img src="images/alarm-clock-icon.png" onclick="toggleElement(\'CircularTimer-1\')" class="alarm-clock-icon"><div id="CircularTimer-1" class="circular-timer-container"><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-1", 43200)</script></div></li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Add to the <amount original_amount="45 g" fraction="45.000000000000" units="g">45 g</amount> from step <amount original_amount="45 g" fraction="45.000000000000" units="g">45 g</amount> of flour and <amount original_amount="45 g" fraction="45.000000000000" units="g">45 g</amount> of water. Stir, cover and set aside at room temperature for ~12 hours.<img src="images/alarm-clock-icon.png" onclick="toggleElement(\'CircularTimer-2\')" class="alarm-clock-icon"><div id="CircularTimer-2" class="circular-timer-container"><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-2", 43200)</script></div></li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Combine <amount original_amount="375 g" fraction="375.000000000000" units="g">375 g</amount> water, <amount original_amount="100 g" fraction="100.000000000000" units="g">100 g</amount> sourdough starter and <amount original_amount="10 g" fraction="10.000000000000" units="g">10 g</amount> salt in a large bowl. Stir with a spatula to combine — it doesn’t have to be uniformly mixed. Add the <amount original_amount="500 g" fraction="500.000000000000" units="g">500 g</amount> flour. Mix again until the flour is completely incorporated. Transfer to a straight-sided vessel (if you have one.) Cover vessel with tea towel or cloth bowl cover and let stand 30 minutes.<img src="images/alarm-clock-icon.png" onclick="toggleElement(\'CircularTimer-3\')" class="alarm-clock-icon"><div id="CircularTimer-3" class="circular-timer-container"><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-3", 1800)</script></div></li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> After 30 minutes have passed, reach into the vessel and pull the dough up and into the center. <img src="images/alarm-clock-icon.png" onclick="toggleElement(\'CircularTimer-4\')" class="alarm-clock-icon"><div id="CircularTimer-4" class="circular-timer-container"><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-4", 1800)</script></div><ul><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Turn the vessel quarter turns and continue this pulling 8 to 10 times. </li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Let the dough rest for another 30 minutes; then repeat the stretching and folding. <img src="images/alarm-clock-icon.png" onclick="toggleElement(\'CircularTimer-5\')" class="alarm-clock-icon"><div id="CircularTimer-5" class="circular-timer-container"><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-5", 1800)</script></div></li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> If possible, repeat this cycle twice more for a total of 4 stretch and folds. </li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> By the 4th cycle, you will notice a huge difference in the texture of the dough: it will be smoother, stronger, and more elastic. </li></ul></li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Cover vessel with a tea towel or bowl cover and set aside to rise at room temperature (70°F/21°C) for 4 to 18 hours (the time will vary depending on the time of year, the strength of your starter, and the temperature of your kitchen) or until the dough has roughly doubled in volume. <img src="images/alarm-clock-icon.png" onclick="toggleElement(\'CircularTimer-6\')" class="alarm-clock-icon"><div id="CircularTimer-6" class="circular-timer-container"><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-6", 14400)</script><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-6", 64800)</script></div><div class="note">    The  Tupperware "What-a-bowl" weighs <amount original_amount="359 grams" fraction="359.000000000000" units="grams">359 grams</amount>.</div></li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Turn the dough out onto a work surface and shape into a rough ball, using as much flour as needed — the dough will be sticky. Using a bench scraper, divide the dough into 2 equal portions. Sprinkle portions with flour. With floured hands, roll each portion into a ball, using the pinkie-edges of your hands to pinch the dough underneath each ball. Transfer each round of dough to a plastic quart container, cover, and store in fridge for at least 6 hours or up to 3 days or transfer to the freezer. <img src="images/alarm-clock-icon.png" onclick="toggleElement(\'CircularTimer-7\')" class="alarm-clock-icon"><div id="CircularTimer-7" class="circular-timer-container"><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-7", 21600)</script></div></li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Pull out a round (or more) of dough from the fridge one hour before you plan on baking. Dust dough with flour and place on a floured work surface. Let sit untouched for about an hour (a little longer or shorter is fine). <img src="images/alarm-clock-icon.png" onclick="toggleElement(\'CircularTimer-8\')" class="alarm-clock-icon"><div id="CircularTimer-8" class="circular-timer-container"><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-8", 3600)</script><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-8", 3600)</script></div></li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Place a Baking Steel or pizza stone in the top third of your oven. Set oven to 550ºF. Heat oven for at least 45 minutes but ideally 1 hour prior to baking. <img src="images/alarm-clock-icon.png" onclick="toggleElement(\'CircularTimer-9\')" class="alarm-clock-icon"><div id="CircularTimer-9" class="circular-timer-container"><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-9", 2700)</script><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-9", 3600)</script></div></li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Gently shape dough into a roughly 10-inch round handling it as minimally as possible. Lay <amount original_amount="a sheet" fraction="1.000000000000" units="sheet">a sheet</amount> of parchment paper on top of a pizza peel. Transfer the dough round to the parchment-lined peel.</li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> To make a classic Margherita-style pizza: Spread <amount original_amount="4 tablespoons" fraction="4.000000000000" units="tablespoons">4 tablespoons</amount> of tomato sauce over the surface of the dough. Top with mozzarella to taste. Sprinkle with parmesan to taste. Drizzle with olive oil. Sprinkle lightly with sea salt.</li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Shimmy the pizza, parchment paper and all into the oven. Bake pizza until top is blistered, about 5-6 minutes. <img src="images/alarm-clock-icon.png" onclick="toggleElement(\'CircularTimer-10\')" class="alarm-clock-icon"><div id="CircularTimer-10" class="circular-timer-container"><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-10", 300)</script><script>new CircularTimer("CircularTimer-10", 360)</script></div></li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Transfer to cutting board. </li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Sprinkle with basil, if you have it. </li><li onclick="handleItemClick(this)"> Cut and serve. Discard parchment paper. </li></ol>' ] );
